Prevent "Symbol not found" error in memcache formula. Fixes #1366

When installing php56-memcache, several of us are seeing:

```
dyld: lazy symbol binding failed: Symbol not found: _mmc_queue_free
  Referenced from: /usr/local/opt/php56-memcache/memcache.so
  Expected in: flat namespace
```

This PR fixes it per @steel-track's work in #1366.

Signed-off-by: Andy Blyler <andy@blyler.cc>

Be more strict about conflicting PHP formulae

At the moment, any formula ending with `php\d\d` will conflict with a php formula upgrade.
This is wrong as some third party provides PHP extensions compatibles with homebrew-php system and could be broken because of this. `blackfire-php70` recipe for instance conflicts on upgrade whereas it should not.

This patch fixes this issue by being more strict about "our self"

Closes #3245.

Closes #2884.

Signed-off-by: Andy Blyler <andy@blyler.cc>

Provide a high level composer method

The `composer` method runs composer with the `--no-interaction` flag
because the user is not able to interact with it during a brew run.

We also add `--verbose` to composer if brew is run with `--verbose`.

We also provide a method for ensuring the Github API token is configured
if we know one.

A method is also provided for running `composer install` with all of the
above taken care of.

Add Adminer from http://www.adminer.org/.

Adminer (formerly phpMinAdmin) is a full-featured database management tool written in PHP. It's a lightweight and easy alternative to phpMyAdmin.

It's just one file but having it in homebrew makes it easier to keep track of updates.

The formula is based on phpmyadmin.rb.

Fixes #1600.

php5{4,5,6}: Restore "--enable-phpdbg" functionality.

There was a bug where adding "--enable-phpdbg" would remove all `./configure`
options, so the "inreplace" on *Makefile* would fail because "INSTALL_IT" was
blank. By ensuring there is not a conditional "args <<" at the end, `./configure`
is no longer blank when adding "--enable-phpdbg".

Fixes #1397.

Closes #1593.

Fix argument expansion when invoking composer

`$*` is problematic because it will blow up if any of the arguments passed with quotes contains spaces. `"$*"` is better, but `"$@"` won't explode if `IFS` is set to something strange, so that's the best solution. See e.g. http://stackoverflow.com/questions/448407/bash-script-to-receive-and-repass-quoted-parameters.

To reproduce, try running `composer config vendor-dir "some path"`, it will fail, but with this change, it works.

Fix shell quoting

The failsafe way to pass shell arguments unmolested is to use "$@", not $* (which will cause words to be re-expanded into separate arguments).

Ability to install php-fpm and apache 2 handler at same time

This change allows the ability to override the disabling of `libphp5.so`
by the `--with-fpm` and `--with-cgi` flags.

A new flag is introduced `--with-apache` which will force the build
of the apache handler even in the presence of `--with-fpm`.

To install `libphp5.so` and php-fpm:

`brew install php5X --with-fpm --with-apache`

PHP 5.6 support

With the release of PHP 5.6a1, I thought it would be best to start using/testing with it by moving support into `homebrew` for usage/testing instead of compiling it by hand and using my own hand-compiled version.

As such, I copied all `php55*` modules into a `php56` counterpart. For any of the modules that have version'd dependencies, such as `php56-couchbase.rb`:

	depends_on 'php56-igbinary' if build.include?('with-igbinary')

...and change to reference the new version.

--

Further, many of the modules seems to have the same data over and over again. There packages all had hardcoded references to the PHP 5.x download location, its checksum, and its version.

In order to test things and bring them into a more DRY configuration, I created an `abstract-php-versions.rb` file (for lack of a better initial name) and created a module that exposes...

 * Download URL
 * Version
 * Checksum information
 * GitHub location
 * GitHub branch name

...and then imported that module into the `php56` formula as well as the `AbstractPhp56Extension` so that they would automatically pick up any change in those values.

As I was unsure whether Homebrew needed the physical formula files to be updated in order to detect a change in configuration (i.e.: `brew outdated`), I tested making changes to the version stored in `abstract-php-versions.rb` and found `brew outdated` properly saw that each dependent module then showed as needing an update.

Fixes for OS 10.5.x Leopard PHP build errors.
PHP Makefile always puts system libraries first

Due to a bug upstream with PHP 5.x (https://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=44294),
the system libraries are always on the build search path before library
paths passed in the by the user. This causes builds to fail on OS 10.5
Leopard, where many system libraries are out-of-date.

Homebrew OpenSSL required to build PHP5.4 on 10.5.

Due to system OpenSSL being too far out-of-date, PHP 5.4 will not build
without --with-homebrew-openssl installation argument. This commit
defaults that option if MacOS.version == :leopard, otherwise users of
newer versions of MacOS are free to use system or Homebrew OpenSSL as
they desire.

Build php-cs-fixer.phar on the fly. Closes #377

@fabpot refuses to release tagged builds for php-cs-fixer because it is
pre-alpha software. As such, it is impossible to follow his daily rebuilds
of the released phar, making it a chore to maintain php-cs-fixer.

This commit retools the work by @davidneimeyer in his php-cs-fixer_installer
repo into a homebrew formulae, allowing us to build the phar file on the fly.
Because of the phar requirements, phar.readonly must be set to off for This
formulae to run properly.

Note that detection of installed php bins may fail if you are using HEAD for
your homebrew-php install.
tabs to spaces

No longer build with inline intl support

As of mxcl/homebrew#03ed757c, icu4c somehow breaks when being built
with php due to undefined symbols. If being built as an extension,
everything works fine.

Rather than deal with people asking why it doesn't work, I am forcing
the installation of of intl as an extension. A warning will be raised
if the intl flag is passed.

Unfortunately, a post-install dependency isn't straightforward, so at
this time this is the best we can do.

If icu4c becomes compliant with PHP building in the future, we can
revert this change and allow users to rebuild with inline intl support.

Force building with dependency upon homebrew-php

Homebrew 0.9.3 added `superenv` as a feature, which essentially
sandboxes all formula installation. Conveniently enough, this breaks
building against things in your path, so rather than allowing people
to build against their own PHP, we just require `homebrew-php`
formulae where necessary.

This commit removes the `with-homebrew-php` flag in favor of the
`without-homebrew-php` flag. I don't pretend to know what that flag
will do, so use it at your own risk.

Remove all pear.conf files from php path

Having a `pear.conf` file appears to block the `./configure` or
`make` step of PHP from writing a `pear` binary, resulting in a
failure to install because `brew install` later calls
`pear config-set`.

We should take a backup of the file and move it back in case of a
failed compile.

Thanks to Andy Blyler, David Rekowski, Todd Bloom, and Mark
Shropshire - and everyone else! - for digging into the issue and
confirming the fix.

php53, php54: fix ambiguous zlib dep

php53 and php54 both have a dependency on "zlib", but because neither
josegonzalez/php nor mxcl/homebrew provide a zlib formula this will
error out for users who don't have a zlib available from somewhere. By
explicitly depending on "homebrew/dupes/zlib", the source of the
dependency can be tracked for users who don't already have it tapped.

Since the zlib dependency was added to fix bugs in 10.8, this also
makes the dependency conditional rather than absolute.

Specifying right phpize for brewed PHP

Installing extensions when the phpize in $PATH is incorrect for that
extension will result in an InvalidPhpizeError. Those without PHP in
their $PATH at all will recieve a UnsupportedPhpApiError, since we
cannot detect `phpize`.

Currently supported are PHP53 and PHP54. Support for other versions
should update line 34 of abstract-php-extension.rb to include the
PHP API Version.

When installing against a Homebrew version of PHP that is not
currently linked, it is possible to circumvent the path using the
`--with-homebrew-php` argument.

Note that calling `system "phpize"` will result in not using the
proper phpize. Instead, `safe_phpize` should be used instead.

description without worrying about side-effects.
